==Old English==
===Etymology 1===
From Germanic ''*mēnōþ-'', from Indo-European ''*mēnōt-'' ‘month, moon’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''mōnath'', Old Saxon ''mānuð'' (Dutch [[maand]]), Old High German ''mānōd'' (German [[Monat]]), Old Norse ''mānaðr'' (Swedish [[månad]]), Gothic [[𐌼𐌴𐌽𐍉𐌸𐍃]].

====Pronunciation====
[[IPA]]: /'mo:naθ/

====Noun====
'''mōnaþ''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''mōnaþas''' or '''mōnaþ''')
# [[month]]

===Etymology 2===
See [[manian]].

====Pronunciation====
[[IPA]]: /'monaθ/

====Verb form====
'''monaþ'''
# variant spelling of the third-person singular present of [[manian]]

